s (590, 990); Relationships (1232, 1237)]\"},{\"summary\":\"Altitude effects (sea level vs mountain top) are used to explain reduced g and therefore reduced weight\",\"explanation\":\"MOUNTAIN TOP functions as a contextual entity to show that gravitational acceleration decreases as one goes up from sea level. This establishes that even on Earth, local g is not perfectly constant, and that changes in g should produce corresponding changes in weight for the same object. [Data: Entities (989, 590); Relationships (1236)]\\n\\nBy connecting altitude-driven g changes to weight through W = mg, the community provides a coherent explanation for why someone’s weight would be slightly lower at higher elevations while their mass remains unchanged. The dataset’s explicit formula support and altitude claim jointly ground this inference. [Data: Entities (993, 590); Relationships (1247, 1236)]\"},{\"summary\":\"Centre of gravity specifies where the weight force is considered to act on a body\",\"explanation\":\"CENTRE OF GRAVITY is defined as the point at which a body’s weight (gravitational force) is considered to act. This locates weight not just as a magnitude and direction, but as a force applied at an effective point for purposes of analyzing motion and equilibrium. [Data: Entities (991); Relationships (1238)]\\n\\nThis relationship provides structural context for force diagrams and torque reasoning: once weight is identified as a force, specifying its point of action becomes essential in many mechanics problems. The dataset explicitly links CENTRE OF GRAVITY to WEIGHT as the action point of the weight force. [Data: Entities (991, 504); Relationships (1238)]\"},{\"summary\":\"Sign conventions for vertical motion connect g to kinematics via acceleration (often negative if up is positive)\",\"explanation\":\"The community includes a kinematics-oriented interpretation: when upward direction is taken as positive, gravitational acceleration appears as a negative acceleration on a v